eri\" Bustos''' (n\u00e9e '''Callahan''') (born October 17, 1961) is an American journalist, healthcare executive, and politician who has served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Illinois's 17th congressional district]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Bustos is the first woman elected to Congress from her district.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/women-candidates-watch-2014-cheri-bustos|title = \u201830 in 30\u2019: Women Candidates to Watch in 2014 \u2013 Cheri Bustos|date = September 12, 2014|accessdate = November 6, 2014|website = MSNBC|publisher = MSNBC|last = Brand|first = Anna}}</ref>\n\nPreviously elected to the [[East Moline, Illinois|East Moline]] City Council in 2007, she defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Bobby Schilling]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2012|2012 congressional election]] and a subsequent [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014|2014 rematch]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/05/cheri-bustos-bobby-schilling-illinois_n_5847032.html|title = Cheri Bustos Defeats Bobby Schilling In Illinois|date = November 5, 2014|accessdate = November 6, 2014|website = The Huffington Post|publisher = The Huffington Post|last = Levine|first = Sam}}</ref> Assigned to the [[House Committee on Agriculture]] and [[House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]], she represents a northwest Illinois constituency anchored by the [[Quad Cities]], [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]], and [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]]. As of the 2014 elections, Bustos is the only Democrat in the Illinois Congressional Delegation not from the Chicago area aside from U.S. Senator [[Dick Durbin]].\n\n== Early life, education, and private sector career ==\nBustos was born in [[Springfield (Illinois)|Springfield]], Illinois, to Gene and Ann Callahan, one of three children. Her father worked for ''[[The State Journal-Register]]'' before entering state politics; he later served as assistant press secretary to Governor [[Samuel H. Shapiro|Samuel Shapiro]], press secretary to Lieutenant Governor [[Paul Simon (politician)|Paul Simon]], and chief of staff to Senator [[Alan Dixon]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/obituaries/ct-gene-callahan-obituary-met-20140805-story.html|title = Gene Callahan, Illinois political aide and MLB lobbyist, 1935\u20132014|date = August 5, 2014|accessdate = November 6, 2014|website = Chicago Tribune|publisher = Chicago Tribune|last = Pearson|first = Rick}}</ref> Her mother worked as a teacher.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url = http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/cheri-bustos--IL-H|title = Cheri Bustos|date = |accessdate = |website = The Wall Street Journal|publisher = The Wall Street Journal|last = |first = }}\n</ref>\n\nShe graduated from [[Springfield High School (Illinois)|Springfield High School]] in 1979. Initially attending [[Illinois College]], she received her bachelor's degree in political science from the [[University of Maryland, College Park]] in 1983 and her master's degree in journalism from the [[University of Illinois, Springfield]] in 1985.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B001286|title = Bustos, Cheri, (1961 \u2013 )|date = |accessdate = November 6, 2014|website = Biographical Directory of the U.S. Congress|publisher = Office of the Historian|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nBustos worked for seventeen years as a reporter and editor for the ''[[Quad-City Times]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> From 2001 to 2007, she worked as senior director of corporate communications for Trinity Regional Health Systems.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://qctimes.com/news/local/cheri-bustos-trinity-health-official-takes-job-in-des-moines/article_d6c65c25-1217-57fc-a03e-1247320a2d56.html|title = Cheri Bustos: Trinity Health official takes job in Des Moines|date = December 6, 2007|accessdate = November 7, 2014|website = The Quad-City Times|publisher = The Quad-City Times|last = Geyer|first = Thomas}}</ref> From 2008 to 2011, she worked as vice president of corporate communications for Iowa Health System; in her last full year, she received overall compensation of $306,295.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tibbetts|first=Ed|title=Trio runs for chance to unseat Schilling|url=http://qctimes.com/news/local/government-and-politics/trio-runs-for-chance-to-unseat-schilling/article_b7d9650e-6b25-11e1-bdfd-001871e3ce6c.html|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=Quad-City Times|date=March 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== East Moline City Council ==\n\n===Elections===\nBustos decided to run for the City Council of [[East Moline]]'s 4th Ward. She won the Democratic primary with 45% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=774679 |title=East Moline, IL Alderman Ward 4-D Primary Race \u2013 Feb 27, 2007 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> She won the general election unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=358582 |title=East Moline, IL Alderman Ward 4 Race \u2013 Apr 17, 2007 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://qctimes.com/news/local/bustos-vacates-east-moline-city-council-seat/article_532a86e0-df04-11e0-82a4-001cc4c03286.html|title= Bustos vacates East Moline City Council seat|author= Barb Ickes|date= September 14, 2011|publisher =''Quad-City Times''|accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref> B In 2011, she won re-election unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=727799 |title=East Moline, IL Alderman Ward 4 Race \u2013 Apr 05, 2011 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nBefore first being elected in 2007, Bustos served on East Moline's Citizen Advisory Committee and the East Moline Plan<!-- not \"Planning\" --> Commission.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} In 2009, Bustos received an Athena Business Women's Award.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=426150|title= 2009 Athena Business Women's Award winners announced|date= February 18, 2009|publisher =''Dispatch-Argus Quad-Cities Online''|accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Bustos secured state and federal money to purchase a $40,000 electronic welcome sign that was placed at the border of East Moline.<ref name=\"qconline\">{{cite web|last=Hocker |first=Lindsay |url=http://www.qconline.com/archives/qco/print_display.php?id=479089 |title=East Moline \u2013 Quad-Cities Online: Local |publisher=Qconline.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Bustos voted for water and sewer rate hikes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hocker |first=Lindsay |url=http://www.qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=506147 |title=East Moline approves modified sewer, water rate hike plan \u2013 Quad-Cities Online: Local |publisher=Qconline.com |date=2010-08-16 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> In January 2011, Bustos expressed interest in charging residents who do not recycle extra fees to lower the city's landfill costs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hocker |first=Lindsay |url=http://www.qconline.com/archives/qco/print_display.php?id=528993 |title=Costs outpace revenue for East Moline garbage collection \u2013 Quad-Cities Online: Local |publisher=Qconline.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> In April 2011, Bustos voted for a budget that raised property taxes 4.9% and raised garbage collection fees, saying, \"these decisions have been made thoughtfully and thoroughly and during the course of 17 open and public budget sessions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/news/opinion/mailbag/article_4bf5cb0c-6491-11e0-90c6-001cc4c002e0.html |title=East Moline manages priorities |publisher=Qctimes.com |date=2011-04-12 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> She supported water and sewage increases.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moline |first=East |url=http://qctimes.com/news/opinion/mailbag/article_8645c52c-999f-11df-bc35-001cc4c002e0.html |title=Just the facts please: Answering tough questions about water and sewer bills in EM |publisher=Qctimes.com |date=2010-07-28 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>\n\nShe has been criticized for voting for a $624,000 project to improve 10th Street in East Moline, which runs adjacent to Bustos's house; the Schilling campaign dubbed it the \"Bustos Parkway\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/news/local/government-and-politics/tv-ad-depicts-bustos-as-working-mom-who-wants-to/article_0ef908f2-f088-11e1-8233-001a4bcf887a.html |title=TV ad depicts Bustos as working mom who wants to fix Washington |publisher=Qctimes.com |date=2012-08-28 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>  Schilling's claim was called  \"reckless, irresponsible fiction\" by the editorial board of the Quad-City Times.\n\nAfter being elected to a second term in May 2011, she resigned in September 2011 to focus on her run for Congress.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hocker|first=Lindsay|title=Cheri Bustos resigns city council seat; mayor seeking replacement|url=http://qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=561069|publisher=Quad Cities Online|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*East Moline Downtown Revitalization Committee (Founded and Chaired)<ref>{{cite news|title=17th U.S. Congressional, Cheri Bustos (D)|url=http://www.pjstar.com/elections/bios/x1957362949/17th-Congressional-Cheri-Bustos-D|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=Peoria Journal-Star|date=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2012#District 17}}\nThe Bustos campaign publicly stated it received the endorsement of about two dozen unions active in the 17th Congressional district, including the Illinois AFL-CIO, AFSCME and the United Auto Workers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schilling's 'Democrat' newsletter angers Bustos|url=http://qctimes.com/news/local/government-and-politics/elections/schilling-s-democrat-newsletter-angers-bustos/article_b7af44c8-1fd8-11e2-9e70-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=October 31, 2012|date=October 26, 2012}}</ref> During the primary, Bustos received the endorsement of U.S. Senator [[Dick Durbin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Giuliani|first=David|title=Durbin backs Bustos for Congress|url=http://www.saukvalley.com/2012/01/04/durbin-backs-bustos-for-congress/avmmu1h/|publisher=Sauk Valley Media|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=January 5, 2012}}</ref> Durbin asked state Senator [[Dave Koehler]] and [[George Gaulrapp]] to drop out of the race to clear the way for Bustos, who is a close family friend of Durbin.<ref name=\"gaulrapp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saukvalley.com/2011/12/29/candidate-durbin-asked-me-to-withdraw/a7z1lbm/ |title=Candidate: Durbin asked me to withdraw |publisher=SaukValley.com |date=2011-12-30 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> Gaulrapp reported that during a meeting with Durbin about withdrawing, Durbin said that Bustos had babysat for his family and was a close friend.<ref name=\"gaulrapp\"/>\nBustos won the Democratic primary on March 20, 2012, defeating [[Freeport, Illinois|Freeport]] Mayor [[George Gaulrapp]] and businessman Greg Aguilar 54%\u201326%-20%.<ref name=\"Sweeny1\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rrstar.com/news/x1612622285/3-seek-Democratic-bid-in-17th-House-District#|title= 3 seek Democratic bid in 17th House District|author= Chuck Sweeny|date= March 15, 2012|publisher =''Rockford Register Star''|accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=734293 |title=IL \u2013 District 17- D Primary Race \u2013 Mar 20, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://qctimes.com/news/local/government-and-politics/elections/bustos-wins-primary/article_344cc112-72fb-11e1-b605-0019bb2963f4.html|title= Bustos wins primary|author= Ed Tibbetts|date= March 20, 2012|publisher =''Quad-City Times''|accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Bustos was one of 39 candidates considered to be the most viable challengers against Republican incumbents to benefit from \"Red to Blue\" program offered by the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]].<ref name=\"RedBlue\">{{cite web|last=Blake|first=Matthew|title=Bustos Draws Contrasts With Schilling On Local Issues|url=http://progressillinois.com/posts/content/2012/07/26/bustos-draws-contrasts-schiling-local-issues|publisher=Progress Illinois|accessdate=October 26, 2012|date=July 30, 2012}}</ref> Bustos was endorsed by the ''Quad-City Times'' for the general election.<ref>{{cite web|author=Times Editorial Board|title=Bustos for Illinois\u2019 17th District|url=http://qctimes.com/news/opinion/editorial/bustos-for-illinois-th-district/article_84b6dc80-2176-11e2-8160-0019bb2963f4.html|publisher=''Quad-City Times''|accessdate=October 31, 2012|date=October 29, 2012}}</ref> In November, she defeated incumbent Republican [[Bobby Schilling]] 53%\u201347%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=712489 |title=IL \u2013 District 17 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>\nShe'd received a significant boost from redistricting, which replaced [[Quincy, Illinois|Quincy]], [[Decatur, Illinois|Decatur]] and the district's portion of [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] with the more Democratic portions of Peoria and Rockford.  She is the first Democrat to represent a significant portion of Peoria since 1927, and only the second Democrat since the 1850s to represent a significant portion of Rockford.\n\n===2014 election===\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2014#District 17}}\nBustos was challenged by Schilling for re-election in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Crow|first=Nick|date=July 13, 2013|title=Election 2014: Bobby Schilling set for rematch with Rep. Cheri Bustos|url=http://www.journalstandard.com/x1580227112/Election-2014-Bobby-Schilling-set-for-rematch-with-Rep-Cheri-Bustos|newspaper=[[The Journal Standard]]|location=Freeport, Illinois|accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the Chicago Tribune editorial board in 2012, Bustos expressed her support for legislation which would cut congressional pay by 10 percent. When asked by a member of the editorial board if she would voluntarily give up 10 percent of her pay should the legislation fail, Bustos said that she would. During the campaign in 2014, she stated:  \"When I was in Chicago, I said something that I shouldn\u2019t have said, but I never said it on the campaign trail. I never made it as a promise to the people in the 17th Congressional District.\"<ref name=\"CTpay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-bustos-congress-edit-0926-20140925-story.html |title=Tribune board calls out U.S. Rep. Cheri Bustos |publisher=Chicagotribune.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/news/local/bustos-admits-mistake-over-pay-comment/article_1f473c2b-1e60-5fd7-bb3b-e8f43f6c2385.html?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter%3Fmobile_touch%3Dtrue |title=Bustos admits mistake over pay comment |publisher=Qctimes.com |date=2014-09-25 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nightengale |first1=Laura |title=Rep. Cheri Bustos concedes that she misspoke |url=http://www.pjstar.com/article/20140912/News/140919653 |publisher=JournalStar |date=12 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Brittany |title=Schilling says Bustos failed to keep promise on cutting pay |url=http://wqad.com/2014/08/22/schilling-says-bustos-failed-to-keep-promise-on-cutting-pay/ |publisher=WQAD |date=22 August 2014}}</ref> The ''Chicago Tribune'' endorsed Schilling for the general election.<ref>(October 14, 2014) \u2013 [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-congress-endorse-edit-1015-20141014-story.html \"Schilling Among Tribune Endorsements for Congress\"]. ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved February 24, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs they did in October 2012, Bustos and Schilling agreed to debate at the [[WQAD-TV]] News 8 studio on October 9, 2014, with Good Morning Quad Cities anchor Jim Mertens serving as moderator.<ref name=WQAD20140513>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Shellie|title=Bustos and Schilling agree to local debate|url=http://wqad.com/2014/05/13/bustos-and-schilling-agree-to-local-debate/|website=WQAD News|publisher=WQAD News|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nBustos defeated Schilling in the November 4 general election, 55%\u201345%.<ref>Vlahos, Nick (November 4, 2014) \u2013 [http://www.pjstar.com/article/20141104/News/141109615 \"Cheri Bustos Wins 17th U.S. House Rematch With Bobby Schilling\"]. ''Peoria Journal-Star''. Retrieved February 24, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Generalelection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionInformation/GetVoteTotals.aspx |title=Illinois General Election 2014|publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections|date=2014-11-04 |accessdate=2015-02-24}}</ref>\n\n===2016 election===\nBustos won re-election to the House in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2016#District 17|2016 general election]], defeating the Republican challenger Patrick Harlan, an insurance agent,<ref>[http://qctimes.com/news/local/government-and-politics/elections/untested-newcomer-challenges-incumbent-in-low-key-race/article_e587986c-2469-57bd-9039-0497d17e4a95.html Untested newcomer challenges incumbent in low-key race]</ref> truck driver, and local Tea Party activist.<ref>[http://www.journalstandard.com/article/20160315/NEWS/160319570 Patrick Harlan wins GOP nomination for 17th Congressional District] (JournalStandard.com)</ref>\n\n===Potential runs for other offices===\nBustos considered running for the U.S. Senate in the [[United States Senate election in Illinois, 2016|2016 election]], but announced in March 2015 that she would not run.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/mar/30/bustos-says-she-wont-run-for-senate-praises-duckwo/ Bustos says she won\u2019t run for Senate, praises Duckworth] (Washington Times)</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, reports emerged that Bustos was a possible candidate for [[Governor of Illinois]] in the [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 election.]]<ref>[http://qctimes.com/news/local/bustos-mentioned-as-possible-governor-candidate/article_8cd822a5-70eb-52c4-924c-305b8e6cfa39.html Bustos mentioned as possible '18 governor candidate] (Quad-City Times)</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n====Committee assignments====\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n\n==Political positions==\nShortly after taking office, Bustos joined the bipartisan [[No Labels|No Labels group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjstar.com/blogs/wordonweb/x1522315411/Cheri-Bustos-No-Labels-and-working-to-compromise |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215065003/http://www.pjstar.com/blogs/wordonweb/x1522315411/Cheri-Bustos-No-Labels-and-working-to-compromise |archivedate=February 15, 2013 }}</ref> Her first sponsored legislation would create a congressional government waste reduction board.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Kaergard |url=http://www.pjstar.com/news/x1037506437/Rep-Cheri-Bustos-introduces-bill-to-streamline-government |title=Rep. Cheri Bustos introduces bill to streamline government \u2013 News \u2013 Journal Star \u2013 Peoria, IL |publisher=Pjstar.com |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wifr.com/news/headlines/Cheri-Bustos-Introduce-First-Piece-of-Legislation-190099871.html?ref=871 |title=Cheri Bustos Introduces Legislation to Reduce Redundancy |publisher=Wifr.com |date=2013-02-06 |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>\n\nBustos wants to create a \"manufacturing triangle\" connecting Peoria, the Quad Cities, and Rockford anchored by Caterpillar, John Deere, and the aerospace industry, respectively. She supports putting in place job-training programs at area community colleges to better prepare workers for skilled jobs in manufacturing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaergard|first=Chris|title=Tight contest expected in 17th District|url=http://www.pjstar.com/news/x2143897891/Tight-contest-expected-in-17th-District|accessdate=November 1, 2012|newspaper=Peoria Journal Star|date=October 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBustos strongly supports the [[Affordable Care Act]] (commonly known as Obamacare). In October 2012, her congressional campaign website said, \"The new reform law is not perfect, but makes real improvements in our health care system. It lowers costs for small businesses and makes sure you have coverage that cannot be taken away. It stops insurance companies from denying coverage of preexisting conditions and allows children to stay on their parents\u2019 health insurance for longer.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Candidate Bio: Cheri Bustos \u2013 17th District|url=http://www.myfoxtwincities.com/story/19777513/candidate-bio-cheri-bustos-17th-district-congress|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=KMSP-TV|date=October 11, 2012}}</ref> Bustos, a Catholic, supports legalized abortion<ref>[http://www.ontheissues.org/IL/Cheri_Bustos_Abortion.htm, Cheri Bustos on Abortion \u2014 ''OnTheIssues.org'']</ref> and the law's [[contraceptive mandate|White House mandate]] on contraception, despite [[Abortion and the Catholic Church|the Church's strong opposition]].<ref name=\"Sweeny2\">{{cite news|last=Sweeny|first=Chuck|title=Chuck Sweeny: House hopeful Bustos weighs in on health, jobs|url=http://www.rrstar.com/insight/x1134102999/Chuck-Sweeny-House-hopeful-Cheri-Bustos-weighs-in-on-health-jobs?zc_p=1|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=Rockford Register Star}}</ref>\n\nBustos opposes a full extension of the [[Bush tax cuts]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweeny|first=Chuck|title=Bobby Schilling, Cheri Bustos spar over job creation|url=http://www.rrstar.com/updates/x1826353795/Bobby-Schilling-Cheri-Bustos-spar-over-job-creation|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=Rockford Register Star|date=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBustos supports a 10% pay cut for members of Congress with no further pay raises until the federal budget is balanced. She has been critical of Republicans' approach to balancing the budget and reducing taxes. Bustos favors reducing waste and fraud, ending \"tax loopholes for companies that ship jobs overseas,\" and ending \"corporate handouts.\"<ref name=\"Spending\">{{cite web|title=Protecting Taxpayers & Reducing the Deficit|url=http://www.cheribustos.com/content/protecting-taxpayers-reducing-deficit|publisher=Cheri Bustos for Congress|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> She does not support lowering salaries or pensions for federal government employees.<ref name=\"galesburg1\">{{cite news|title=17th District debate: Schilling, Bustos square off|url=http://www.galesburg.com/news/x1292872956/17th-District-debate-Schilling-Bustos-square-off|accessdate=October 26, 2012|newspaper=Galesburg Register-Mail|date=October 11, 2012|author=Ward, Joe|author2=Cheung, Ariel}}</ref>\n\nBustos supports the [[DREAM Act]].<ref name=\"Sweeny2\" />\n\nDuring a debate, Bustos opposed the three trade agreements approved by Congress in 2011 as \"NAFTA-style\" and said they would result in job losses for Illinois.<ref name=\"galesburg1\"/>\n\nBustos wants to change [[No Child Left Behind]] to offer more assistance for teachers while de-emphasizing \"[[teaching to the test]],\" expand [[Head Start Program|Head Start]], reform student loans to address rising tuition costs, \"protect and expand college scholarships like [[Pell Grants]]\" and \"improve vocational and job training opportunities for children who decide not to attend college.\"<ref name=\"Education\">{{cite web|title=Education|url=http://www.cheribustos.com/content/education|publisher=Cheri Bustos for Congress|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 responding to [[People v. Turner]], Bustos claimed a need for more women in congress to bring sexual assault to the forefront.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/17/us/politics/congress-stanford-letter.html|title=House Members Unite to Read Stanford Rape Victim\u2019s Letter|last=Aguilera|first=Jasmine|date=2016-06-16|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=2016-06-16 |quote=This is why we need more women}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBustos is married to Gerry Bustos, the Rock Island County Sheriff and commander of the Quad City Bomb Squad.<ref>[http://www.saukvalley.com/2014/09/13/new-sheriff-in-rock-island-county-has-familiar-name/a16r76x/ New sheriff in Rock Island County has familiar name]</ref> They have three grown sons and two grandchildren.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://bustos.house.gov/ Representative Cheri Bustos] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.cheribustos.com/ Cheri Bustos for Congress]\n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Illinois/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Cheri_Bustos_%5BD-17%5D}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = B001286 | ballot = Cheri_Bustos | nndb = | votesmart = 134964 | govtrac